						<summary>

						<p>On a slab built into the platform of the Pañchamukhi Hanumantadēva temple.</p>						

						<p>1841 A.D.</p>						

						<p>These seem to be pilgrims' records. One in Kannḍa characters mentions the name Dattātrēya Avadhūta. This is followed by Nāgarī writing recording the date Śaka 1763, Plava, Vaiśākha va. 30. This corresponds to 1841 A.D., May 20.</p>						

						<p>In the upper portion of the slab is engraved a short inscription in Arabic comprising religious text with an amulet of the figure 20 at the end (which is also incorrect), used for the supplication of the dead. This leads one to infer that the record is probably an epitaph of religious interest only.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
